body:
`PrimInt` is too strict and only works for primitive integer types in map feedback and observer.

Actually, the map can be considered as an array of a generic type. For example, an edge map is an array of `u8`.

This pull request removes `PrimInt`, but enforces a minimal set of required traits instead, including `PartialEq`, `Bounded`, `BitAnd`, and `BitOr`.

By doing this, LibAFL offers better flexibility to users and allows them to define a map with customized structures that are collected from the program under testing.

The following codes are related to one of my use cases:

```rust
#[derive(Debug, Default, Copy, Clone, PartialEq)]
struct CustomEntry {}

impl Bounded for CustomEntry { ... }

let custom_map: &mut [CustomEntry] = [...];
let custom_map_observer = StdMapObserver::new("foo", custom_map);

// Customized feedback, feedback state, and reducer can be implemented accordingly
```
